comment: The mantra I am present means a lot to me. I say that to myself a few times. About 1 month ago I made the desicion to not end my own life. Even though I really wanted to. The mantra: 'I am present' gives energy to fight my demons. Anyone who is struggling know that you are not alone and you will get through this hold on.

My 30 days so far have not been perfect. I fall off because I do alot of other training and I tend to push yoga aside in favor of weight training or cardio. But when I do it I remember why I need it and that yoga is the last thing I should be pushing aside. I definitely need yoga in my life. It awakens my mind, heart and body and frees my soul from all the burdens and pain I have experienced in life. I love to fly in my yoga poses and feel weightless and happy. Even if once I step off the mat I forget that feeling. Eveytime I'm on the mat I feel and see a light shining inside me and it give me so much peace. The same peace I see when I watch my children playing and laughing and learning. Thank You for Yoga camp. I think this is one of my favorite 30 day challenges.

I started doing yoga after my therapist mentioned it. Apparently I'm not really good at paying attention to my body and what I feel INSIDE my body. I stumbled across Adriene and began the Beginners yoga starting out 4 times a week for about 3-4 weeks. Then, I started this yoga camp. I never ever ever thought I would be doing yoga but here I am on day 10 and I haven't missed a day and it feels SO good. It seems like I'm waking up my body after years of sleeping muscles. I can feel them stretch without it hurting and Adriene's encouragement, humor (sometimes I have to stop the videos to laugh with her) has opened my eyes to something I never knew I needed. I love how she explains things so well and how she always wants us to "find what feels good", I'm very overweight and just knowing that in these practices I can just do what feels good and find out what my body needs is perfect for me. Adriene, if you find yourself reading this sometime, please know you are so appreciated and I'm so thankful for your teachings (and humor). You ROCK!

Thank you for another great session Adrienne;  Yoga camp has 
already been an amazing and eye opening experience on many different levels...outside of the obvious physical and mental health benefits most of us come to expect from regular practice, there is something about participating in yoga camp, something about committing ourselves to 30 days of (hopefully..lol) uninterrupted and continuous practice that allows one to access a subtle level of perception that is at once  extremely powerful yet paradoxically faint and elusive..one gets the distinct impression that this perception, or perhaps more accurately, the deep  and fundementally interconnected fabric reality that we are able to perceive, has been there all along right under our noses; but much like one of those old three dimensional stereogram posters, if you look too hard, (if you try too hard) the 3 d picture disappears and your just looking a collection dots...i belive yoga helps us to defocalize our sometimes narrow and constricted survival -based awareness while allowing us to reconnect with the natural intuitive feeling that sees past the illusion of separation and into the depths the psyche, the fabric of reality,  and the true nature of  consciousness...much gratitude for all your hard work and dedication Adrienne... Hello friends!
I just wanted to share a small story and say how grateful I am for these videos. I've been following Yoga With Adriene for about 3 years now, and several videos have helped me through my depression and anxiety but none like today. I jumped on the Yoga Camp train a little late, but I just finished Day 10 and the mantra "I am present" meant so much to me. I was struggling heavily today, trapped in the past and toxic thoughts, and I didn't even want to do yoga. I pulled up the video and groaned when I saw it was almost 40 minutes long, and I had a really difficult time settling in. I was fidgety and I had a hard time focusing on my breath, still thinking toxic thoughts and trying not to cry, but I just kept repeating "I am present." By the end of the video, I wasn't even focused on my problems anymore. I had smiled and laughed during the video, and when it was finished I was groaning that it was over! 
Anyway, I'm not usually big into sharing but I really did want to share this and send a big thank you to Adriene for these awesome videos!

I really wanted to find extra space during this practise and realised that instead of folding in pigeon as I normally would do, I could (and did) use it as a heart opener. I wanted to shine the fun of my day out into my world. It was beautiful to learn something new by holding back and really pay attention.

I choose to be present is everyday situations. And just try to really pay attention to the world around me.
